purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffering a critical examination of the nature of co-produced research, this important new book draws on materials and case studies from the ESRC funded project ‘Imagine – connecting communities through research’. Outlining a community development approach to co-production, which privileges community agency, the editors link with wider debates about the role of universities within communities. With policy makers in mind, contributors discuss in clear and accessible language what co-production between community groups and academics can achieve. The book will be valuable for practitioners within community contexts, and researchers interested in working with communities, activists, and artists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunity and college. 0aResearchxSocial aspects. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAslam, Shabina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBell, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonner, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Milton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButtery, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiles, Prue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurch, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEryigit-Madzwamuse, Suna, econtributor.4ct